# Type rules

## Semantic aliases over bare primitives

Where a string/number has clear domain meaning — use a named type alias, not bare `string` or `number`.

**Example:**

```ts
// ❌ Bad
const cache = new Map<string, URL>();
function parse(url: string): URL { ... }

// ✅ Good
type UrlString = string;

const cache = new Map<UrlString, URL>();
function parse(url: UrlString): URL { ... }
```

**When to add an alias:** same meaning repeated in signatures, Map/Record keys, or type fields — add type in `types.ts` with short JSDoc.

**When to keep simple:** one-off params with obvious meaning from arg name can stay `string`/`number`; interfaces mirroring external API (e.g. Navigation) may stay without aliases.
